          "tool_calls": 10,
          "final_message": "The fix is verified. Here's the summary:\n\n---\n\n## The Bug\n\nIn `requests/sessions.py` line 428:\n\n```python\nmethod = builtin_str(method)\n```\n\nIn **Python 3**, `builtin_str` is `str`. When you call `str(b'GET')` on a bytes object, Python returns the **string representation** of the bytes literal — `\"b'GET'\"` — not `\"GET\"`. Then `.upper()` turns that into `\"B'GET'\"`, which is not a valid HTTP method, hence the 404.\n\nIn **Python 2**, `builtin_str` is `str` which *is* bytes, so `str(b'GET')` just gives `'GET'` — it works by accident.\n\n## The Fix\n\nApplied at `requests/sessions.py:428`:\n\n```python\nif isinstance(method, bytes):\n    method = method.decode()\nelse:\n    method = builtin_str(method)\n```\n\nThis checks if `method` is a bytes object first and decodes it properly, only falling through to `builtin_str()` for native strings and other types.\n\n## Why the other `builtin_str` calls are safe\n\nThe other uses in `models.py` all pass **integers** (e.g., `builtin_str(body.tell())`, `builtin_str(length)`), which convert cleanly to strings via `str()` in both Python 2 and 3.\n\n## The neutronclient side\n\nWhile this fix handles the symptom, you're right that neutronclient calling `safe_encode_list` on all args (including the method) is the upstream cause. With this fix, requests will tolerate it gracefully.",
